node.text:
Plate carrier load outs can scale in price quickly. Depending on what pouches, accessories, and armor you add. But for $500-700 you can have a modern and minimalist setup with quality rifle plates. Can you get a Chinese-made plate carrier that looks like something from 2005 and a set of steel “armor” for a little cheaper? Yes. There’s always a cheaper option… but that’s not always the best option in relation to your money’s worth.
-
I’ll always choose American with quality warranty and support. 🇺🇸
-

node.text:
Running a 10.3 MK18 from close out to 400m with a Razor 1-6 HD II. While short barrels aren’t optimal for longer ranges, it can still be done. Good ammo and knowing your holds helps. I’m using 55g Winchester ball which… isn’t the best for this. But still doable. This is one of my favorite LPVOs as it has the brightest center dot of any scope I’ve used.
-
Got them in stock at @trexarms
-

The new generation of Sidecar supports these options much more efficiently.
-
That’s what we’re all about.

node.text:
Shot-calling is something every basic carbine/pistol class should cover. It is essential for self-diagnosis in improving marksmanship, recoil control, and shooting speed. I don’t think certain skills make someone “advanced” or “level 2” but if there was one thing that elevates some shooters above others, it’s shot-calling. Make sure you shoot a target far enough away so you can’t see the impact before you walk up. This is why I like to go back 25m+, make my call, then walk up and paste hits.
-
This is a segment from my 3 hour carbine class that is available for free at TREX-ARMS.COM.
-

node.text:
Standing around wearing night vision is cool. You know what’s a lot cooler? Being able to sprint through the woods with NODs without tripping… changing batteries without taking your helmet off… applying a tourniquet without activating any IR light… changing focus on the fly to properly PID… knowing to remove your IR patches, goon tape, and cover exposed Tegris to not reflect IR to a near-peer night vision user… knowing exactly how many clicks it is on a PEQ/LA5 to go from high power illuminator to low power laser only… being able to move without constantly looking down at your feet.
-
Just like the popular staircase meme going around, a lot of people want to skip the basics of NVG use and go straight to CQB and “goon stuff”. I’ve been guilty of this too. Stop. Work the basics.
-

Doing some non-rehearsed CQB with Michael from CS during Copperhead within hostile territory. I’ve never practiced any CQB with Michael in particular, but we had to make it work regardless. He’s a former Marine, I’m a civilian. We used minimal verbals, covered angles as best as we could as a two man element, pulled security after checking each room, and moved pretty quickly. Is it perfect? Heck no. Could it be better? Absolutely. Will I ever teach CQB? No way. Will I practice it? Of course. Should you take a class and understand core principles? It’s not a bad idea. Where should you go? These dudes are putting out accessible courses to citizens:

node.text:
Want to get off the flat range or save money on bullets while still repping your kit? Airsoft is the best method right now besides an expensive professionally-organized FoF course with UTM. I used all this kit pictured over the course of 2 days and 2 nights which is a lot more reps and time than a couple hour range session once a week. Not to mention; most of my time was movement, communication, map-reading, PID, and white/IR light discipline than actually shooting BBs. Milsim events are one of the most underrated training venues for citizens who want to go beyond a shot timer and drills on the range.
-
Not pictured is my belt with dump pouch, CAT, and speed reload 556 carrier. Because reasons.
-

Plate carrier load outs can scale in price quickly. Depending on what pouches, accessories, and armor you add. But for $500-700 you can have a modern and minimalist setup with quality rifle plates. Can you get a Chinese-made plate carrier that looks like something from 2005 and a set of steel “armor” for a little cheaper? Yes. There’s always a cheaper option… but that’s not always the best option in relation to your money’s worth.
-
I’ll always choose American with quality warranty and support. 🇺🇸

node.text:
We are back in business! After months of issues surrounding the original AC1 launch, AC-Uno debacle, lawsuit, finding new manufacturers and establishing protocols: the AC1 is back. This morning we restocked over 4000 medium plate carriers between ranger green, Multicam original, and Multicam Arid. With the other sizes and colors restocking in the months to come. They’re being manufactured in batches, so we’ll get smalls in such-and-such a color, then larges, mediums, etc. We have two vetted American manufacturers pumping these out for us and the quality is sick. Pictured is one of our QC stations where we check over batches of AC1s that come in.
